text: ‚Äã¬†@chaptap8376¬† The ukrainian famine of 1932 was due to numerous reasons,most obviously that imperial russia was underdeveloped, leading to frequent famines since the 1850s. On top of that a combination of international economic and military pressure+bad weather which led to bad harvests for a few years+bad policy from the government+many rich farmers burning millions of tons of grain out of spite. Could the communist government handled it better? Sure they could have, but it cant be solely blamed on them. Also fun fact when the bolsheviks took power in 1917 the average russian lifespan was less than 40 years, while by the time Stalin died in 1953 it surpassed 60, so there is that.

text:
Soviet gulags had 18 million imprisoned. About 1.5 million died. Countless more from cruel government rule. The communist party in cahoots with KGB secret police; making people 'dissappear'.

Whole towns experimented on and forced labor or worse. It was a brutal time and the fiction is far closer to the truth than one would hope.
author: @lazycouch1

text: ¬†@lazycouch1¬† gulags are just russian prisons. Under the bolsheviks the total amount of prisoners never surpassed more than 2.1 million and the highest amount of people imprisoned for political crimes(during prewar and war period) is estimated at around 25%(so around 500000 people, most of which were suspected of being collaborators with the axis). Compared to the hundreds of thousands of people of japanese descent in the US which were imprisoned for the same reason, this number doesnt seem particularly high. As for the death count, the mortality rate in prisons drastically decreased compared to the tsarist era before, decreasing from 30% to a mere few %(except during the war years when the government offered prisoners to fight in the war in exchange for lowering their sentence, which led to an increase in the amount of deaths). Who would have thought that when analyzing history you gotta look at the context and wider picture before making a conclusion?
